{
  "texts": [
    "However, a key limitation of ML-based fossil image classification/segmentation studies is their reliance on novel hand-crafted features, requiring expert knowledge and extensive experience in anatomical analysis, thereby limiting their widespread adoption (Smith et al. 2022; Lai et al. 2021).",
    "Deep Learning (Ansari et al. 2023; Ma et al. 2024; Ansari et al. 2024 Ansari et al., 2022)) overcomes some of the limitations of ML-based approaches by extracting task-specific features directly from data, eliminating the dependence on manually crafted features.",
    "Consequently, DL algorithms have emerged as transformative tools within several domains, including medical imaging, robotics, geoscience, and pharmacology etc (Ansari et al. 2021; Marchant et al. 2020; Ansari et al. 2023; Askr et al. 2023; Ansari et al. 2022; Huang et al. 2023; Ansari et al. 2022; Altaheri et al. 2023; Ansari et al. 2023; Yaqoob et al. 2024).",
    "The ability of DL-based approaches to automatically learn features and differentiate between relatively nuanced groupings of objects in image data makes them highly amenable towards automated fossil segmentation and classification tasks.",
    "In paleontology, subtle morphological differences can delineate species, providing major challenges for automated classification (Allmon 1992; Ballard et al. 2021; Romero et al. 2020; Funk 2018; Trier et al. 2019; Allmon 2013; Roberts et al. 2006; Carvalho et al. 2020; Jayachandran et al. 2024; Hughes 2009)."
  ]
}